Rating: 4
So delicious! Made this for a small dinner party last night in Vermont after the guests had been skiing all day - it was definitely a hit and just the comfort food they needed. I added 2 cloves of minced garlic and 1/4 cup chopped fresh chives while sauteing the prosciutto, then I added juice from 1/2 lemon, 1.5 cups of peas, and 1/4 cup chopped fresh basil when it came time to mix everything together. Finally I added 1/4 cup of the shaved parmesan to the pasta dish all together before serving to the guests with some additional parmesan on top for garnish. I also used fresh fettuccine since I couldn't find tagliatelle. I served this with some homemade rosemary artisan bread and a salad of mixed greens, green apples, candied pecans and goat cheese with a homemade maple syrup dijon mustard vinaigrette....a few bottles of red wine made this the perfect winter meal!

Rating: 4
Certainly followed the recipe as written 98% although I don't measure with great accuracy. Either way, I have two comments: 1 -- didn't like the handling of the prosciutto which diminished its magic. Would suggest broiling/baking until crisp then adding just as serving. 2 -- boiled the pasta a half-hour or so ahead so it had turned into a somewhat rubbery pan-shaped mass as pasta will do. Never mind: stir it into the quite liquidy sauce and in a minute when it has heated through, the texture is PERFECT -- creamy, not at all dry. Great! Fabulous flavor -- present, but subtle. Re-heats beautifully too.

